I think when people think of "buying a boat" they associatively imagine like women, partying. but then all stories of boat owners are them having horrifying near death experiences getting stuck far from coast during nocturnal thunderstorms, hallucinating sirens alone at sea, etc.

Literally every guy with a boat I know has a "the scariest moment of my entire life" story about having to dive down in the water to fix a motor or thick fog and all old boat life guys have cryptic stories about actual sea monsters or seeing ghosts that they allude to when drunk.

Olympic weightlifting equipment seems so intuitive in the specific dimensions of barbells, the plates, etc. that it appears as one of those things that are "discovered" rather than "invented", like mathematics. Seems surreal it originates in the 20th century rather than eternity.

Saw this picture of someone called Andy Jackson making what was supposedly some of the best weightlifting equipment ever produced in history in his basement and it reminded me how some world-class products basically rely on one single small town autist making stuff in his garage.
